SYPHILIS - AUSTRALIA (02): (QUEENSLAND) REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
***************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Tue 2 Dec 2014
Source: ABC (Australian Broadcasting Corporation) [edited]
http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-12-03/mount-isa-health-unit-not-expecting-short-term/5936434


The director of the sexual health unit in Mount Isa [Queensland, Australia] says it has seen an increase in syphilis infection rates this year [2014].

The unit is currently dealing with an outbreak of the sexually transmitted disease and has implemented new regimes to get people tested and treated.

Dr Arun Menon said last year [2013] in the north-west it had about 45 cases of infectious syphilis but it was on the rise. "We're testing about the same number of people in the various locations where we are providing services," Dr Menon said. "So far this year [2014] in the north-west we've had about 50 cases and another 20 that have been linked to the north-west in different parts of Queensland. These are individuals who are from here but they have been diagnosed elsewhere."

He said there was still a long battle ahead to get on top of the disease. "There is a concern because we are still having babies who are being born who are at high risk of having syphilis and we are trying to again get the population to come in and be tested and we are trying to encourage doctors and nurses to test," he said. "I don't think we'll see a reduction anytime soon, I think this will carry on being a long-term problem and that is what we are doing - we are approaching it as a long-term problem."

[Byline: Kate Stephens]

